What is an n-gram?¶

An n-gram is a contiguous sequence of n items from a given sample of text or speech. Here, 'n' can be any integer. When n is 1, we refer to it as a "unigram". Similarly, a 2-gram (bigram) is a two-word sequence of words like "please turn", "turn your", and so on, and a 3-gram (trigram) is a three-word sequence of words like "please turn your", "turn your computer", etc.

Methodology¶

Mentions of loss and damage were searched for across all UNFCCC input documents. This involved automatically translating documents into English using the Google Translate API before identifying as many potential linguistic expressions of the meta-concept to feed in as rules for a search process. The methodology is explained in detail here and the relevant linguistic input file is available for download here.
